Getting Started In Data Science¶

This was a solo project by Alexander Glatfelter

Hello there!
This is a tutorial for absolute beginners on how to get started with a Data Science project. In this we'll focus on the five major steps of Data Science:

  • Data Collection - How to obtain raw data
  • Data Cleaning - How to change raw data into usable data
  • Exploratory Analysis & Visualization - How we look at the data
  • Hypothesis Testing and Modeling - How we analyze the data fully
  • Drawing Conclusions - What we will learn from the previous steps

Data Science may seem like an imposing thing but in the end, Data Science is about trying to answer a question you have.

If you think about it, when you want an anwser to a question, you would follow the same steps.

  • You would research your topic
  • Gather everything you think is important and organize it
  • Synthesize ideas from that data
  • Then draw your conclusion from the whole.

Data Science is the same, the only difference is the methods and algorithms of Data Science let you do this with massive amounts of data.

There's this nice thing about Data Science, a lot of the tools are available to you for free. This tutorial was created in a Jupyter Notebook, and all of the libraries we'll use can be downloaded with the commands in this tutorial. The only thing you'll need is a computer, the internet, and a little bit of time.

Whenever I use a method or a function in this tutorial, I'll frame it like this, these will be links to it's documentation, so that if you're following along and have an issue, you can click on it to find out a little more about it.

No Data Science experience is necessary to follow this tutorial, and we'll go step by step through some easily accessable example data. That way, you can follow along if you want. The only thing I'll assume is that you know basic programming concepts and have a vague familiarity with Python.

We'll be using easily accessable data for this tutorial, and all the data will have the theme of Football.

We'll get our first batch of data from a standard website. While there's numerous websites and even a Google Dataset Search to get pre-existing sets of data from, I'd like to show you how to get that data in the wild.

There will be nothing pre-processed or collected for us in the beginning of this tutorial, we're going to pick the proverbial apple from the tree ourselves.

For this first part, we're going to use this website: https://umterps.com/sports/football/stats/2021

This is the University of Maryland's 2021 Statistics Page. If you take a quick look, there's no "download dataset" or anything like that. It's just a simple webpage like any other with graphics, tables, ads, and links to other pages.

Data Cleaning¶

Now we'll introduce the concept of Data Cleaning which basically means transforming raw data into something useful. The nice thing is that there are already tools available to handle this task.

We're going to use a library called beautiful soup, to help us process the block of webpage HTML.

This will clean up the sprawling HTML code and make it nice(er) and neat(er) to read:

In [4]:
from bs4 import BeautifulSoup
#This will read the raw data of the website, and parse it as HTML!
soup = BeautifulSoup(UMD_2021.content, 'html.parser')
#Then we can use it's prettify() in order to space it out and make it easier to read.

Let's see a brief section of what it would look like if we ran .prettify() on the massive html text block.

Normally it would start a new line for each \n, but it's acting a little weird on my system. But we can still see how the page is supposed to be laid out now. Each \n represents the end of one line, and the beginning of another. If we take a look:

soup.prettify()

While we'll double check, it can be safe to say that we've gotten all the data on this website, now we just need to Tidy the data.

Roughly speaking, Tidy Data is the concept that all data should be organized in easily processable rows. The idea encompasses a lot of important concepts, so reading up on it should be something you should look into if you're interested in data science.

But I'll give you the most important basics:

  • Each observation forms a Row (Horizontal)
  • Each measurement (aka variable or feature) is a column
  • Each type of observation has its own table

Note: I highly recommend reading the link just above, as it explains the concepts and ideals in more depth.

So what's the next step? Cleaning and Tidying that data! This is what I would consider one of the most important steps in Data Science, and probably the longest step in general.

So here's what we'll do, we'll go through each table, fix any missing data we find, get rid of any unecessary data, reshape the tables into something more easily usable, and make sure all the measurement units line up. Then we'll do that for all of the other years that the data is available.

If you're thinking "that's a good bit of work" you're right. So we'll make functions to process the data rather than type all the commands by hand each time. We'll work through the first table to see what we need to do.

Ok, using the idea of tidy data, we're going to transform this table into a more organized dataset.
We could consider this a "single" observation. So we could consider this table the "Average Team Statistics For the Year 2021 at University Of Maryland, College Park."
That means all of this information is one observation on the "Average Team Statistics for UMD Football." We need to transform all of this data into a single row, so that we could compare the various year's statistics. We also should move the Opponent data to its own dataframe by year.

So we'll start by transpose-ing the data, this will make 1 "entry" for our year, 2021

Note: We're going to assign the transpose to a new variable. This is helpful because it prevents you from modifiying your original data. That way, if you need to approach from another angle, you can just assign the original data to a new variable and try again.

In [10]:
UMD2021_Team_Avg = UMD2021_Team.transpose()

Whoops! Rename went through and swaped every collumn named "Total TOT" to "Total Scored." This is not what we wanted to do. Luckily, we didn't ask it to do it "in place" so our original data is untouched.

The solution we're looking for, is to alter the actual array that makes up our table. Everything we do here will be "in place" however, so make sure you're working on a copy before you irrevocably change your data. Remember, some websites will block you if you send too many GET requests, so keeping a copy of the untouched pure data is optimal (unless you have storage issues, etc)

We'll be accessing the columns.array info, and changing each index manually. We do this by entering:

In [15]:
UMD2021_Team_Avg.columns.array[2] = "Total Points Scored"

Much much better. But why did I rename everything?
So, full disclosure, I don't know very much about football. ¯\(ツ)/¯

That's why I wanted to learn more about it from analysis.

What this means is that while I was processing the data, I was also looking the values and learning what they meant and how they were derived. In any data science project, you should know the units of your measurements. It's important for all the data to line up, and if a unit changes midway through some observations, you'll have a problem later on when you're exploring the data.

So now onto the last step, renaming and separating the Maryland Data from the Opponent Data. First we'll change the "MARYLAND" and "Opponents OPP" ids into something more informative.

Now we can use the rename function and it will work perfectly for our needs:

Something I wanted to point out:
I was tempted to rename these as UMD 2021 and Opponents 2021, but remember tidy data. I would be committing a double whammy of mistakes, because:

  • I would be combining two features of information (UMD & YEAR)
  • I would be including the observation type (UMD Team) in the data (UMD & YEAR)

What needs to be done is to change both of these entries to the year: 2021, and store them each in their own observation table. I'll do this one at a time so as to keep it simple.

One way we could construct our new dataframe would be to concat the data to another dataframe. However this method won't work well for large amounts of data. I'll put why in tiny text for the more technically minded, and the rest can move on to the next step.
Every time you append you're actually making a memory copy of the dataframe you're appending to and from, so it leads to quadratic memory usage. Also there's a lot of issues with indexing and type issues. The best way is to make a list and then transform it into a data frame, which is what we're going to do. This link to stack overflow explains it in more depth than I could.

So what we'll do is use .loc or .iloc in order to access the row of UMD data we've renamed to 2021, convert it to a series (which for our intents and purposes is basically an array), and then append that to a list. We'll then make a dataframe out of it later, once we have the rest of the data.

So there's two ways we could get this data:

  • We could create parsing code to check if the 'Result' was a W or an L, and add +1 accordingly
  • We could get the data from the second to last row and fifth column, split the data, and then place it accordingly.

The first option uses an "if" loop that checks the character in the column. Simple and effective.

The second option is a chance to utilize python regular expressions which is a little more complicated, and therefore a little more interesting.

So we'll design a system of functions to process the data, then we can combine them in another function, and then use that function to process the rest of the websites, just like last time.

We'll import the regex library by importing re, then we'll get the size of the "Game by Game: Results" numpy table by using .shape.

This will return a tuple with the length and width of the table, telling us how many spots down our last entry is, then we can run a simple regular expression (regex) on it to pull out the data we want:

So we're looking for the second to last entry, and the fourth over value to get the Win - Loss Record, in addition to this, we'll add another column for "Total Attendence" and fill that in as well.

def add_win_loss_attendence(url ,year,UMD_data, OPP_data):
    raw_web = requests.get(url)
    soup = BeautifulSoup(raw_web.content, 'html.parser')
    html_str_table = soup.find('table')
    table = pd.read_html(str(soup))
    # Get the tuple (X,Y) from the shape of the table, we can access this by shape[0] (X) and shape[1] (Y)
    shape = table[11].shape
    # Get the spot where the Win-Loss Record is located
    spot = table[11].iloc[shape[0]-2,4]
    # Run a regex on the value.  This is looking for a (digit)-(digit) in the spot, stored as an index
    Win = re.search("(\d)-(\d)", spot)
    # Add the data we regexed to the win, losses.
    UMD_data.loc[year,'Wins'] = Win[1]
    UMD_data.loc[year,'Losses'] = Win[2]
    # Also the opponents are the opposite of UMD's Wins
    OPP_data.loc[year,'Wins'] = Win[2]
    OPP_data.loc[year,'Losses'] = Win[1]
    # Add the total attendence to the table as well
    UMD_data.loc[year,'Total Attendence'] = table[11].iloc[shape[0]-1,6]
    UMD_data.loc[year,'Total Attendence'] = table[11].iloc[shape[0]-1,6]

The line is the linear regression, which in simple terms is a line that has minimized the distance from each point to itself.
These distances are called the residuals, and this line could be considered the line of best fit for our data.

There's something to notice here, you might think that this line is a bit higher than it should be, this is because we have an outlier in our data.

The point up at seven wins stands out from the rest of the data, so it's altering the linear regression of the data. This is important because it brings up two important concepts:

  • Linear regression can be affected by outliers
  • Small data sets can lead to less accurate models

Hypothesis Testing and Modeling¶

So what's next?

We'll we've obtained a sample of data, cleaned it, and viewed an aspect of it, next we should consider what we want to learn about this data. In statistics and data science, this has a special term: Hypothesis Testing.

At its core Hypothesis Testing has two main concepts: The Null Hypothesis and the Alternative Hypothesis.

  • The Null Hypothesis could be considered the "default" belief. It's the current idea that you're challenging.
  • The Alternative Hypothesis is the new idea you're proposing.

So with the data we have available, what hypothesis will I want to test?

  • In what I've read online, you need to rely on both passing and rushing to win, since one isn't necessarily better than the other.

So the null hypothesis would be that this is true, and the alternative hypothesis would be that this is false.

In order to test this, we'll need to model how passing and rushing affect the win rate. We'll build a simple OLS model to test this.

Note: Hypothesis testing is much more complex than this simple concept I've mentioned here, and it's well worth reading up on about it.

For our data set we can use an Ordinary Least Squares (OLS) method of regression to build a model to figure this out.
We can use another library statsmodels in order perform this OLS rather easily. We'll be using the .ols to do this.
Fitting an OLS with this library is rather intuitive, as it uses a formula method that is easy to understand:

formula = DEPENDENT VARIABLE ~ INDEPENDENT VARIABLE #1 * INDEPENDENT VARIABLE #2 ... * INDEPENDENT VARIABLE #N

So in this case it will be: Wins ~ Rushing Yards * Rushing Touch Downs.
statsmodels by using * as the link between dependent variables the report will list out how much that particular aspect affected the other parts of the OLS.

Note: statsmodels can be very picky about it's input data. If you're having trouble with getting ols to accept your values from your dataframe, then redefine them as lists like I did here.

In [59]:
import statsmodels.formula.api as stat
win = UMD_Year_Avg_Stats['Wins'].tolist()
rushyard = UMD_Year_Avg_Stats['Rushing Yards Gained'].tolist()
rushtouch = UMD_Year_Avg_Stats['Rushing Touchdowns'].tolist() 
# performing the regression
# and fitting the model
stats  = stat.ols(formula="win ~ rushyard * rushtouch", data=UMD_Year_Avg_Stats).fit()
print(stats.summary())

So when this pops up you may not know where to start, but we'll break it down step by step:
also the error is spoiler for a future discussion

Starting from the top right:

  • Dep. Variable: Win The dependent variable - What we're modelling for
  • Model: OLS - What we're using, Ordinary Least Squares
  • Method: Least Squares - Again, it's using least squares, nothing unusual here
  • Date & Time: Self explanatory
  • No of Observations: 7 - How many observations we've viewed
  • Df Residuals : 3 - This is essentially our degrees of freedom, or Observations - Variables - 1
  • Df Model: 3 - This is the number of variables we're using to predict
  • Covariance Type: nonrobust - This can either be robust or nonrobust. What nonrobust means is that we weren't able to use the covariance of our data to remove some of the variables

Now on the top left:

  • R-Squared: 0.401 - This is how much our independent variables affected our dependent variable. In this case the rushing yard total and the touchdown total resulted in a 40% change in our win variable.
  • Adj. R-Squared: -0.199 - R-squared is funny, if you kept adding variables to model the data, it would only go up in value. However some of those variables may not be helpful in the analysis. This value tells us that one of our variables isn't pulling its weight in the regression.
  • F-statistic: 0.6687 - This is a value you need to use with an F-table to find out if your variables are statistically significant. We won't worry about this for now.
  • Prob(F-Statistic): 0.626 - We could consider this regression to also be a hypothesis test, in that case we would say the null hypothesis is that the independent variables have no effect on the dependent variable. This is a percentage chance of the null hypothesis being right. So what this is telling us, is that there's a high probability that the wins aren't strongly affected by rushing information.
  • Log-Likelihood: -11.713 - In short, this is how well the model fits the data, higher numbers mean the model fits better.
  • AIC & BIC: These are similar to Log-Likelihood as they're measuring how well the models work in linear regression. Discussing these would be a bit lengthy, so it's best to read up on AIC and BIC when you have time.

Now we can look at the middle, which usually gives the data we're looking for. Let copy the data so you don't have to keep scrolling up:

coef std err t P>{t} [0.025 0.975]
Intercept 2.7416 5.251 0.522 0.638 -13.969 19.453
rushyard -0.0027 0.006 -0.457 0.679 -0.021 0.016
rushtouch 0.3242 0.430 0.754 0.506 -1.044 1.692
rushyard:rushtouch 2.827e-05 0.000 0.169 0.876 -0.001 0.001

Intercept is the model as if we ran it with no independent variables. It's analagous to y = 0x + B, so in this case it would be our B.

rushyard, rushtouch are the independent results of each variable.

rushyard:rushtouch is the effect that rushyard and rushtouch had on each other.

Each of these have a column of results. From left to right we have:

  • coef: The coefficient of each variable, or how much that variable has an effect on the result. This would be the m in y = mx + B.
  • std err: This is the measure of standard deviation for the coefficient over all points of data.
  • t: This is essentially how far the measured value is away from the expected value created by the model caused by standard error. It's used in the next part which is:
  • P > |t| : This is similar in concept to the F-statistic. P is calculated using t, and calculates the chance that your dependent variable is not changed by the independent variable. It is a percentage chance of the null hypothesis being correct: that the variables had no effect.
  • [0.025 0.975]: This is a 95% confidence interval of our data. This is the range of values within two standard deviations of our mean. In simpler terms, it means anything smaller than the 0.025 value or larger than the 0.975 value are unlikely to occur and could be considered outliers.

Now the last bit: | | | | | |-------------------------------|-----|-----------------|--------| |Omnibus: |nan |Durbin-Watson: |1.567 | |Prob(Omnibus): |nan |Jarque-Bera (JB):|0.005 | |Skew: |0.009|Prob(JB): |0.997 | |Kurtosis: |2.867|Cond. No. |4.05e+05|

  • Omnibus: A measurement of how normal our residuals are, with a value of 0 meaning perfectly normal. This means that the residuals shouldn't have any unusual patterns of their own. We have nan due to the small sample size.
  • Prob(Omnibus): This is the probability that our residuals are normally distributed.
  • Skew: This is a measurement of how evenly distributed our data is, or how symmetrical it is.
  • Kurtosis: The measurement of how light or heavily tailed our data is. In simple terms this is how much our data moves away from the linear regression at the ends, or how many outliers there are. Higher numbers mean a better normality.
  • Durbin-Watson: How evenly our errors are distributed throughout our data. It's more complicated than that, so you can read up on it here.
  • Jarque-Bera (JB): This is similar to the Omnibus, a measurement of how normal the residuals are.
  • Prob(JB): This is similar to Prob(Omnibus), a percent chance on how normal the residuals are.
  • Condition No.: Essentially this is a measurement that our independent variables are directly affecting each other and changing our results. For example if A helps B, and we're measuring A + B, then B already has A's help, and we're double counting that.

Interpretation & Conclusion¶

Let's try interpret this information and see what we can find out. First let's take a look at the F-Statistics for both models:

  • Rushing: F-statistic: 0.6687, Prob (F-statistic): 0.626
  • Passing: F-statistic: 2.678, Prob (F-statistic): 0.220

The F-Statistic measures how statistically significant the variables were to the model, and the Probability of it is a measurement of the chance that the variables were insignificant.

As we see, the passing model had a much higher statistic and a much lower probability that the data was insignificant. This means that, as a whole, the passing model is much more likely to be a better model of the data.

Let's also take a look at the P values for each:

  • Rushing:
    • rushyard p-value: 0.679
    • rushtouch p-value: 0.506
  • Passing:
    • passyard p-value: 0.232
    • passtouch p-value: 0.449

Each of the p-values show what's the percentage chance that the variable has no effect on wins. Clearly lower value means more of chance for the variable to have effect.

We can see that both of the rushing values are rather high, especially when you consider a "suitable" p-value is usually around .05. Passing is also high, but both of those values are lower than the Rushing values, meaning that in their model, they have more impact.

If you had a much better defined model, you could see how much each value affected wins by the co-efficient, as that would represent how much of a win you would obtain by rushing one yard.

So what's our conclusion?¶

Hypothesis Testing is concluded by rejecting the null hypothesis or not rejecting it. Note that not rejecting isn't accepting the null hypothesis, that would mean something quite different.

What not rejecting means is that we don't have enough evidience yet to disprove the null hypothesis, if you can't disprove something that doesn't mean you automatically accept it.

Looking at our model, we see very low F-Statistics and high Probability(F-Statistics), each p-value is WAY above what would be considered acceptable values (.05), and our coefficents are all not helpful.

This leads me to say that I am not rejecting the Null Hypothesis, simply due to the fact that the model lacks enough data to draw conclusions.

What I will say is that I saw a slight lean in the information that passing fits better, but that means statistically nothing.
read: doesn't mean anything*

At most it's an insight for further investigation.

Always remember, if it turns out your data is inconclusive, never try to shoehorn it into a form that demonstrates something. The data science is still science, we're trying to develop experiments to learn new things.

If you alter your data so that you get a better P-value, or a high F-Statistic, then the there's almost no point to the experimen, you would be drawing conclusions from misleading data.

What could we do to do better?¶

Increase the amount of data used in the model.

As mentioned in the introduction, there are numerous websites and even a Google Dataset Search you can use to get pre-collected or even pre-cleaned data.

We could also get the years prior to 2015 and develop code to clean and tidy those datasets, and then re-run the code. Or we could get other collegate football team information and add that to the model.

Recap¶

In this document we have:

  • Obtained data from a scraping a website
  • Cleaned and tidied that data to make it useful
  • Seen common errors and issues when you explore and visualize that data.
  • Used that data to make a simple model to draw conclusions from
  • Arrived at a conclusion and discussed what it really meant

To be honest, this is just the tip of the iceberg and there's a ton of other really amazing concepts around, and each one is worth learning about.

While some of higher level ideas of Data Science and Machine Learning seem really advanced or difficult, you should remember that these were built step by step with the same concepts we've learned about in this tutorial.

No matter what they're trying to reduce error and create a more accurate model, much like the OLS we did.

I hope this was a good introduction to the bare bones of data science, and that you'll proceed to learn more about what this discipline can do.
